{"cursor":"14635","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Anatomy\n| Name = Spermat Latin = spermatozoon GraySubject = 258 GrayPage = 1243 Image =\n| Sperm-egg.jpg Caption = A sperm cell attempts to penetrate an ovum coat to\n| fertilize it. Image2 =Complete_diagram_of_a_human_spermatozoa_en.svg Width =\n| 350 Caption2 = Diagram of a human spermatozoon System = MeshName = Spermatozoa\n| MeshNumber = A05.360.490.890 Dorlands = nine/000957142 DorlandsID =\n| Spermatozoa\n}}\n\nA 'spermatozoon' (alternate spelling 'spermatozoÃ¶n'; plural 'spermatozoa'; from\n\"seed\" and \"living being\") is a motile sperm cell, or moving form of the haploid\ncell that is the male gamete. A spermatozoon joins an ovum to form a zygote. (A\nzygote is a single cell, with a complete set of chromosomes, that normally\ndevelops into an embryo.)\n\nSperm cells contribute approximately half of the nuclear genetic information to\nthe diploid offspring (excluding, in most cases, mitochondrial DNA). In mammals,\nthe sex of the offspring is determined by the sperm cell: a spermatozoon bearing\na Y chromosome will lead to a male (XY) offspring, while one bearing an X\nchromosome will lead to a female (XX) offspringâthe X chromosome. Sperm cells\nwere first observed by Anton van Leeuwenhoek in 1677.\n","linknr":442,"url":"Spermatozoa","recorded":1362502046,"links":80,"instances":["biology","biology","biology","biology"],"pdf":["http://eprints.maths.ox.ac.uk/860/1/human_sperm.pdf","http://eprints.maths.ox.ac.uk/860/1/human_sperm.pdf"],"categories":["Germ cells","Semen","Human cells","Fertility"],"headings":["Mammalian spermatozoan structure, function, and size","Spermatozoa in other organisms","Spermatozoa production in mammals","Spermatozoa activation","Artificial storage","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Sperm-egg.jpg/350px-Sperm-egg.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9f/Complete_diagram_of_a_huma